&gt; I think it is reasonable to ask that a test with an 
&gt; assumption fail (or at least be marked ignored) if *all* the 
&gt; test data fails the assumption.  A test that never executes 
&gt; because its assumption is never satisfied is 
&gt; counterproductive.  In this case, a failure would alert the 
&gt; user could fix the assumption, update the test data, or 
&gt; remove the test entirely if it&#39;s no longer needed.
